annotation: As I think the King's Gambit was a popular opening during the 19th century.
If I played I prefer 3.Nf3 instead of 3.Bc4 because it avoids the annoying 3...Qh4+.
What was that? I think that Kieseritsky tried to activate the light squared bishop on a6-f1 diagonal by some moves later where the white King was.
As I think 5.Nf3 followed by 6.Bb3 and 7.d3 (or d4 if possible) will give white a better control over the center. On the other hand it was recapturing the pawn he offered in the second move.
Getting the control over the center is very important while it was attacking the pawn on e4.
Developing a horse while attacking to the Queen but 3.Nf3 is better according to me.
Black was trying to a breakthrough with 8...Ng3+. According to my opinion it is better not to move the same piece in the opening moves I like 7...c6 here.
The queen was threatening to both the bishop and the horse. 9.Nf5 would stop that for a while.
It was the only way to protect both pieces.
Trying to create some space for the light squared bishop as well as a pawn moves towards the center.

An aggressive counterattack! Black could easily cut the bishop and there will be a huge blank squares around the white king. Because the king has been moved it would be not difficult to launch an attack from the kingside.
Anderssen was ignoring the piece and trying to attack the queen.
12...Qg6 is forced.
Again he was forcing 13.Qg5.
He had to move the horse otherwise the Queen is trapped with 15.Bxf4. It had no better place than its home square.
Black was threatening 16.Qxb2 followed by capturing the trapped rook.
It stopped the threat but 16...b4 would force to move the same knight again.
It was taking the control over the a7-g1 diagonal while attacking to the rook on g1.
He was giving up both the pawn and the rook but can you see how smoothly the white pieces come towards the black king?
By this move anyone can obviously see that black was becoming very greedy to obtain the rooks without offering anything.
19...Qxg1 would not be as vulnerable as 19...Bxg1 as I see because Bc5 was exerting pressure on Bd6.
I would not like that move because white would do 20.Nc7+ if only he was badly needing the rook. And it was a blunder and a mate in 3 for white. Can you locate it?
There was no other possible moves.
All the thing needed to Anderssen was a CHECK as the black king's squares were attacked by the knights..
Willingly or not black had to capture it or to put 22.Ne7. Both are a mate in next move.
Though White was 21 points down the game was ended in favor of White.
An opening i'm not using anymore as my personal database shows a % of win higher for black.

Ruy Lopez opening was one of my favorite when the game was played. The White Bishop gets there to volunteerily get harassed by a6-b5 pawns and be re-routed on a better square (a4-b3-c2) which weakens slightly the black queenside and create holes for a counter-punch on a-file or get the center with maneuvers like c3-d4.
Classical defense to exert pressure on e4 as 4.Bxc6 5. Nxe5 is countered easily by Qd4 and gives back the pawn on tempo.

Clearly planned the c3-d4 setup but its not a good time to play it. Black could play now 4...Nxe4 without being too much harassed with my pieces as the further retreat 5...Nd6 forces white to remove the Bishop or exchange it.

Better 4.0-0 to pursue the development of pieces and make it a trap on e4 for black.

Looks like a good development move but in fact this move gives back the edge to white. As white had previously shown their intent of d4 with the preparation move c3 it appear obvious the black bishop will be kicked of his square and that Bb6 or Bb4 still allows white a good control of the center via d4-e4 pawns. 

4...Be7 is more solid as it prevents potential pin on f6 and he won't be thrown away on squares his activity is almost useless.
Natural development move.

The idea 6.Bxc6 7.Nxe5 isnt good as e-pawns will be exchanged and open the position for black who has an advantage of development (3 minor pieces vs 2 that's the price to pay for the earlier c3 move)

This move claims the center as explained before.

I think this move was made automatically as it makes good sense to release pressure but also allows me a good center. 

Although i think the retreat 6...Bb6 is better as 7.d5 is meeted by 7...Ne7 and forces white to defend the e4 pawn and get an advantage of space that black could counter sooner or later by trying to destroy the pawn chain d5-e4.

7.dxe5 isnt any better as one of the e-pawns will fall after knight capture and the other one will be isolated on the e-file which makes it tough to defend and needs all white resource to keep it.
The best move i guess.
Here a risky plan: Kick out the knight from d5 so i can push my pawns on the 5th row and create an outpost on the potentially weak d6 square. Alternate 8.Nc3 or 8.d5 are also possible.
8...Ne4 is a better outpost as an eventual d5 can be met by Nxf2 and force the Exchange on f2.
Black is struggled in his pieces placement and white will try anything to achieve it.
9...Nce7 is better because it doesnt allow 10.d5 to white and achieve their goal of getting d-e pawns on 5th row.

A clear blunder. White's plan is to pin the knight so an eventual d5-d6 pawn advance will allow him at best a good outpost. Fact is: 10....d5 kills completely white's play and after 11.exd6 spatial advantage is almost gone.

Better is 10.d5 Na5 11.Bd3 to keep the center without being countered and accept the loss of a tempo by Bishop retreat.
Probably the fear of the pin makes opponent missing ...d5. I won't do same mistake twice.

More active is 11...Na5 to gain tempo on the bishop. 

When pieces are struggled like this and that you haven't a target big enough to claim a clear victory develop your pieces actively and wait to complete the development befpre attacking as weak pieces will stay weak for a while and a too quick counter-punch can backfire to you as you opened squares to achieve it.
Achieved plan since Bg5: Outpost on d6. Alternate 12.Nc3 or Re1 are still possible.

Maybe it was the best common sense move but I dont like it as it allows a definitive outpost at d6 for the pawn. Maybe they traded for materialistic reasons but 13.dxc7 gains a pawn but the outpost is lost and far more important than the gain of c7 as it paralyzes black activity for a while. 

I think 12...Nec6 or Ng6 is better. Maybe.
This knight has no future except targeting a pawn already protected. I still maintain 13.Nec6 or Ng6 idea.
Exposes Nf5 weakness...
14...g6 also possible. It weakens kingside but at least keeps the knight on more active square.

Claiming the e-file with a bunch of black pieces struggling (like the queen). Maybe 15.Bxh6 was even stronger as it opens the g-file for a direct attack to the king and i have plenty of pieces to achieve it.
Forced.
Making the d6 outpost worthy while keeping the queen struggled. The rook threat wasnt my first intention as it doesnt play a great role in the game.

Expected 16...Ng4 to exert pressure on f2 and make more active a flank knight. The idea is to advance a pawn and develop white bishop which i think is a wrong idea as it's slow and that being struggled requires more energetic measures to avoid a slump.
Achieved development.
Explained earlier
An uneasy mating threat to meet. 18...Nxg5 isnt possible as 19.Bxg5 traps on a discover the queen.
I think 18...f5 is better as the pawn doesnt create new hole on f6 as g6 does and supported by the flanked knight. I would almost be forced to capture the rook to get something from it.
Picked a good outpost while showing the weakness created on f6 and a potential fork on c7.
Monstruous blunder as black doesnt see the f6 queen fork. Better was 19...Ng4 to protect f6 while attacking f2.
What else?

Here i missed a deadly combination: 22. Bf6+ Kg8 23.Qh3! and then black is forced to give check on white king to avoid the mate on g7 or h7 with 23...Bxf2+ 24.Kxf2 Ng4+ 25.Qxg4 h5.

I've found another solution of my own although.
Trades an important defensive piece for a not-so good bishop and clears the way for the powerful knight.

It's a lost game for black but maybe 22...Bxf2 with idea of Ng4+ slows it a bit. 22...dxe7 allows a passed pawn to white if black doesnt sacrifice the rook on e7 for bishop + pawn which could be a good asset.
Still missed the 23.Bf6+ 24.Qh3 setup.
Get myself a more complicated game as this mate can be turned-off by the simple ...Bxe4.
Not seen the upcoming mate obviously.
Great finish for a good game.
This is a game I lost. I underestimated my opponent's attack. It's a Sicilian Rossolimo variation. I never thought it was a particularly offensive variation but I had to change my mind.

I have a solid center a rook on an open file I can't complain overall. The thing is my pieces are drifting away from the king-side and I am not thinking of aggressive resources of my opponent at all. I think this move is already a bit unconventional. First 10. ... a5 fit better the idea of queen-side attack. Second Black has to think about what will happen when White will push forward the e-pawn. And I am not doing that.
This is an attempt to open the center which I consider now not likely to work.
And that's the reason. White's pieces are better placed.
I did not resign to the knight dominating the center. This weakens the castle: the Black should worry more about gaining some space to maneuver before opening the lines.
The bitter truth. e6 will become a far too easy target if the Black takes the pawn otherwise.
This unduly concedes f5. The Black must call the far-away forces to the king-side: 17. … Rbe8 18. Qh6 Qf7. The c4 pawn and the black bishop are laughable.

Trying to breath. This is an educational example: one of those situations in which it really matters what rook you move.
… Rbd8 21. Re3 Kh8 22. Ne7 Rg8 23. Nxg8 Rxg8 somehow resisted.
Black resigns. So if you're attacked don't forget: seek space and bring the pieces to the bombed area!
Book so far.
Unnecessarily blocks in the KB and cramps Black's position. 3... B-B4 is the correct move.
Bernstein quite properly tucks away his King befor engaging in complications.
Another bad move. 4... N-B3 or even 4... N-R3 to add extra protection to the KBP would allow 5... B-K2 and 6... O-O getting the King to a relatively safe spot.
Bernstein takes immediate advantage pressuring KB7 at once.
Opening the diagonal fully for the Bishop and ensuring his King will never have a safe haven.
Forcing the monarch to bestir himself.
The only square.
Adding force to the attack.
7... N-B4 isn't any better. Black's position is shattered already just 7 moves in.
Setting up a vicious discovery.
White could win slowly with 9 BxRP or quickly with...
...this move.
In spite of removing the Q Black is still mated in 2 moves.
Forcing the King to...
...this square where...
...this Pawn finishes the game with a flourish.
This is the first correspondence chess game that I have won. Looking back it was actually shorter than I remember it.

At the time this was my favorite opening as Black a variation of the Hippopotamus Opening. It allows White a good control over the center and Black good defense and a castled King with hopes of counter-attack on the center.
3. c4 is what I expected.
Now my Kingside has two gaping holes.
I would rather my Bishop be on g7.
I do not remember why I did this move. Developing or 6. ... 0-0 would have been stronger.
Planning to pin the Queen to his King.
Oblivious.
Freeing my White Bishop and attacking his.
Stopping Qh3.
This begins his Checkmate Ceremony.
Kd1?? Kf1 would have saved him.
I hope you enjoyed! Please comment and rate. Thanks to Knackers for this great game!
?  The black knight was just there.  Is black hoping white blunders?  Is black's position so perfect it cannot be improved?
Ok that is just bizarre.  Dance of the knights.
Finally!  A bold pawn move!  :)
Hm I don't see it.  Knight for two pawns?  Oh when black moves the rook white can snag the h5 pawn too.  Three pawns.  I guess it is a fair exchange then.  20 moves before the first capture.
Mmpf.  d4 and b4 are now easy pickings.
:)  White makes back one of the pawns except c5 goes bye.
Black decides to trade rooks.
Shoot.  Pinning the queen against the rook with the bishop would have been nice.
It isn't a credible threat if black can munch pawns.
Ouch!  Bxe4!  White sacrifices the entire western hemisphere's pawns plus e4.
Check with the knight doesn't work because of that black bishop.  Otherwise it would be game over.
White's queen is lost.  White was right to resign.

I started with the grand prix but sort of transferred into the Sicilian main line.

Better is 10. Qxc3

23... Nxg3? is alot worse as he would give up both Knights for a Rook.

I really don't like when my opponent plays the french defense. That's why I joined the tournament "French battles". I hoped to discover the weaknesses of the defense by playing it.
Recently I started to play the Tarrasch variation which at first sight is complex but actually is quite comfortable for the white.
Black avoids resolution of the center. Closed variation.
Botvinnik Variation.

So far the main ideas of the Tarrasch variation were more or less deployed. Neither of us 2 knew enough theory to know the continuation.
Now the White comes to the first serious decision: taking the pawn e.p. implies also taking the c-pawn and playing an open sharp position. I believed the black would gain too much space and initiative and prepared myself for a long war.
Bc2 was better: it spares the rook one tempo to get into play. However I liked the threat of Qc2 after the Black has castled.

The Black wants to free up f8 for the knight. I wonder if Re8 would have been better to this purpose: d8 might be used by the queen as well and from e8 the rook would defend the critical e6 point. 12. ... ; Qc7 with the ideas b5-b4 Rb8 Nb6 would have maybe been better.
Why? This will only attract the attackers!
The net effect of the last 5 moves of the black has been to bring the knight from d7 to g6. Meanwhile the White gained a passed pawn an open file and is sharpening the blades.
The idea of 11. Bb1 was to play Qc2 and this move is inconsistent with the plan. Now Qc2 would be purposeless given the defenders of f5. The queen must find another way.
The knight is content of having weakened the castle and duly comes back to base.
Another knight comes into play. For the moment the black Ng6 is blocked along with the knight e7 defending it.
The idea at the time was probably Nf1-g3/d3. The simple 22. Nh4 was more to the point.

This is a mistake. The f5 pawn must not fall!
The computer analysis suggest the continuation: Qe6 23. Bc2 (which again proves the inconsistency of 11. Bb1) Rc8 24. Nf3 Rc6 25. Bd2 Rb6 26. b3 Bc7 27. Nh4 Kh8 28. Rae1 Bb5 29. Rg3
Be6+ was an option but I did not want to swap pieces after Bf7.
No! After 25. Bxg6 Nxg6 26. Rxg6 Qxg6 27. Nxf4 the white gets one piece.
That's a dead pawn walking.
Better 29. ... h5 30. Qxh5 Qe6 31. Qg4 Qxg4 32. Rxg4
To let the rook in.

This is a blunder. Ra6 was necessary. The computer suggests the continuation:

32. Qf5 Qc6 33. Qxd3 Bxg6 34. Qe2 Be4 35. Bf4 Qe6 36. Raf1 Qh3+ 37. Bh2 Bg5 38. Rg3 Qe6 39. c4
The white wins sooner with 33. Rf1 Bf7 34. Ng5 Bf6 35. Nh7+ Kg8 36. Nxf6+ Kh8 37. gxf7 Qc8 38. Qe8+ Qxe8 39. Nxe8 Kh7 40. f8=Q Rxe8 41. Qxe8
best 35. Bxg5 Bxg6 36. Rxf6+ gxf6 37. Bh6+ Qg7 38. Qxf6+ Ke8 39. Qxg7 Ra6 40. Bg5 Be4+ 41. Kg1 Re6 42. Qg8+ Kd7 43. Qf7+ Kc6 44. Qxe6+ Kb7 45. Bd2

If you look at how the white played you will notice an excessive avoidance of complication. There is always time to give check: I could have gained more with Qd5+. The white wins anyway and that's what made me spare energy at this point.

That a nice trap isn't it? :D however again the white missed the best sale. Look at this:

45. Rc6+ Kd7 46. Rd6+ Ke8 47. Rb6 Bf5 48. Rxf5 Rxb2 49. Rf8+ Kd7 50. Rf7+ Kc8 51. Rc6+ Kd8 52. Ra6 Rc2 53. Ra8+ Rc8 54. Rf8+ Kc7 55. Raxc8+
Sometimes less is more: a single pawn is enough in the end.

Vidmar uses a Budapest Gambit a relatively new line at the time. Rubinstein proceeds to badly mishandle the game.

Rubinstein's greedy insistence on maintaining the Pawn will be punished. Modern players know that often times the best way to deal with a gambit is to return the Pawn at the appropriate time in return for a positional advantage.
Forcing an ugly weakness in Rubinstein's Pawn structure.
Aggressively posting his Queen.
Forcing the removal of the advanced KP.
Returning the Knight to its natural square with tempo.
Opening a line to develop his last minor piece.
Tucking his King away before engaging in complications.
Removing Rubinstein's strongly centralized Knight.
Planting his own Knight in a central outpost.
Forcing Rubinstein's King towards the open spaces.
A beautiful sacrifice breaking apart the Pawn-chain shielding the White King.
Now threatening 18... N-N6 ch winning Rubinstein's Q on the discovered attack.
Now 19... N-N6 dbl ch would win the White KR.
Beginning a furious King-hunt.
Driving the King further away from his friends.
Closing in.
The logical follow-up.
Another sacrifice this one drawing the King onto a square from which a deadly double check can be issued.
Rubinstein graciously resigns rather than play out the checkmate.

This opening is called the Schotch Gambit.  It is used by players like me who enjoy having a large attack.  The opening is sometimes considered reckless as most attacking chances are because an oppenent doesn't know the opening and falls into one of its many traps.
I now have the advantage that I wanted when I played this in the opening.  I have the pawn back and I have doubled up his c pawns.
This was a big blunder on Black's part.
Now White is up 2 pawns and holds a strong pawn in the center.
This move forces 14...Be8 which allows for White to liquidate the position to better his advantage.

Now it is even more clear that white has the winning position.  He is up two pawns and has both of his Knights active. Black's Rook is hemmed in and his Knight is badly placed.  The Bishop pair isn't enough compensation for Black's postion and material disadvantage.
I challange him to give up the Bishop pair but he decides not to.
19...Bxd5? doesn't work. 20. exd5 Bxb4 21. dxe6 fxe6.  The smoke clears with White having the advantage.
I think this deserves an !! because it lets me trade off the Bishop pair with me having the only Bishop left.
?? This helps me even more. He can't hold onto the Bishop in any case but 22... Rd8 may have been better.
He can't stop my pawn from Queening without a Rook sac but that leaves me with a Bishop a Knight and 2 future pass pawns. He resigns instead of hoping I would blunder.

At last I have a game of my own to annotate.  It looked as though my game was going nowhere until after a queen trade my rooks somehow ended up on my opponent's second rank.  To have just one rook there can be a bone in the throat to my opponent but two ....... well read on.  Gameknot Analysis is provided for this game as follows:- http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=15155377&fb=1&rnd=0.7747064337826831

7. ..... 0-0 both sides now castle on the kingside.
9. Ne5 - this knight move brings about a trade off of minor pieces.
11. Bxe5 - I got rid of white's knight on e5.  Although it is replaced by white's dsb I am more than happy to trade off Fou Lenoir for it.
13. dxe5 - and I do.  Although a white pawn now occupies e5 it is doubled.  At least white does not have his lsb so it may not be quite so easy for white to mount an attack on h7.
14. ...... c5 - I decided to expand on the queenside.
16. ...... a6 - a Witch Ejection Plan is in place.  I call the enemy Queen the Wicked Witch of the West because she can be very wicked if allowed to be.

19. ...... Rfb8 - although I am temporarily a pawn down the Witch is skewered in front of her b2 pawn and she cannot retreat to defend it so I get the pawn back and give my opponent that bone in the throat.
21. a4 - natcht.
24. ..... Rdd2 - now here is the double-up. Already g2 is under fire and the white knight is too far away to help.
25. ...... Rxg2+  - a pawn is a pawn.  I now decide to drive the WK to the edge of the board and nail him there.

28. ....... c4 - I trick white into believing that the c pawn is bound for Glendadom.  My queen is known as Glenda.  Ah but this is a space clearance for my knight.   White should start feeling very cold soon and you will soon see why.
29. a5 - white is tempted to push that passer along.  You would never believe that that innocuous looking steed on d7 is the Chessic Grim Reaper Old Matey in disguise would you?
30. a6 - he still pushes on that pawn but the square e4 is undefended and my steed now lands on it.  White should have played Nb5 here.  He will now cop Old Matey.

31. Red1 - white can only delay the mate with the self-immolating Re2.  He decided not to do this and my knight comes to g6.  White decided to resign on the grounds of Unavoidable Mate here and I pick up 10 useful rating points.

This game was originally intended to be a fun random inter-team game that doesn't matter.  So I just played any random move I saw without much thought.  And as it turns out it's probably the greatest game I've ever played.  There's nothing to be proud of by winning over a lower rated opponent but what makes this game amazing is the moves that were played.  
According to computer analysis my opponent played a "perfect" game and I was the only one to make a "mistake".  And yet I still won.          

I know using computer engine analysis afterward to help analyze this game is kind of cheap but if you were to seriously look at the position after 17. Nxg5 and try to analyze it yourself (and figure out the forced win) the position is so complex your mind will blow.  Personally I spent at least 6 hours just playing the game from move 21 to the end and afterward I spent 2-3 hours analyzing it before I gave up amid the complexities and used a computer engine.  And what I found was shocking.  I played the computer from move 17 onwards and eventually (with take-backs) won several times and after every variation it would take the computer a long time before it figured out that it was black was in fact losing. Eventually the computer was still refusing to say that 17. Nxg5 was winning for white and at best said it was a draw.  I seriously hope it wins but may still be a draw and such complexity is beyond my comprehension.
Already starting to look interesting. Save your time for the later developments instead of this lame position.
!? I would have preferred Nc6 allowing freedom for the bishop. But I think black intends Nb6.

!? At this point I just wanted to throw everything at black's king and see what happens. I didn't want to spend much time thinking because I didn't care whether I won or lost.  That would change very soon.

! I don't know what got into me this game but I made this move with minimal thought. As it turns out it deserves an exclamation mark for the pressure it puts on black and is eventually a very important pawn in allowing 17. Nxg5 to win.  If Bxe5 then 14. dxe6 generating pressure on black's king.  (14. ... fxe6 Qxe6+ wins a bishop)
!?  More surprises.  My entire goal was to point everything at black's king and think of nothing else. In fact I made this move essentially without thinking as well.
In hindsight g5 was better because my bishop has to move.   This move wasn't bad at all in the circumstances however because it takes the b5 square out of my control.

!? Funny I intended to retreat with this move and allow black to create his own attack. Of course the side effect was the opening of the e file.  That was because after a few minutes' thinking I couldn't come up with anything better. (I thought about f4 but I didn't believe it would do anything useful. I like to keep my king hidden.) Instead this is what happened:

!! Like I said I didn't care about the outcome of the game.  My trial version 2800 elo Shredder engine said this was a mistake! And I punished its incorrect judgement by beating it.
 I highly doubt any computer whether it's Rybka or Fritz would ever play this because it clearly looks as though white hasn't much to attack/threaten with and black has a solid defense.
Forced.  Otherwise Qh4! wins the game.
! Another computer-defying move.  Somehow it just came naturally to me.  This forces a passive knight to be traded by one of black's important defenders.

Now black could also have played Be7.  White still wins if 19. ... Be7 by 20. Qd4!! Kg6 21. Ng3 Kxg5 **(if Qxd5 4. Bxf6 Qxd4 5. Bxd4 Bd6 6. Nxf5 Kxf5 and white is up a pawn with black's king stranded in the centre)** 22. Re5! Kg6 23. Qf4! (lots of checkmate threats) Ng7 24. Nxf5 Bg5 25. Qg4 and I think black looks pretty screwed with a looming f4 threat.

The only other move was Re8 but it is uncertain whether that move avoids a loss (too complicated to analyze conclusively even for my computer!).  
Possible variations after Re8 after hours of analysis:
Draw: 21. Rxe8 Qxe8 22. Bxf6 Kxf6 23. Qh4+  Draw by perpetual check.
Similar to the Rh8 variation:
21. Re1 Rxe4 22. Rxe4 Be7 23. Qd4 Qd6  and my computer posts a draw by repetition.
(24. Rg4 Kf8 25. Rg3 Rd8 26. Qh4 Ke8 27. Qh8+ Kd7 and draw)
Not sure if there's a move the computer missed that wins as in the case of the Rh8 move the winning moves which I found by myself (my computer couldn't find it even after hours of searching).
But a possible continuation without drawing: 24. Rf4 Rh8 25. h4! Re8 26. Too many possibilities and complications to analyze. But if 24. Rf4 c6! I think black might survive and draw. (but not conclusively sure)
Heres one: 24. Re5 and I haven't quite had enough time to analyze this neither has the computer (the computer still says black is slightly better); I found a draw through this that I forgot the sequence but I'm not sure if it's possible to win through this.  

If anyone can conclusively prove a draw or a win for white please add your input!  This is the best I can do.
! At this point I immediately saw the possibility of an h-pawn advance threatening black's king all the time.
! Forcing a rook trade and then I have an active rook while his is hidden behind his queen.
This move must be done to eliminate the deadly pin on the knight.

! This creates many threats and keeps the knight pinned.  I chose Qc3! over Qd4 because it gives my queen more flexibility with the whole row 3 available and in addition guards the e1 square which will will be black's only threat later on.
This move also must be played because black really needs the rook to survive.
! White's threats never stop.  This prevents any of black's pieces from moving except the black rook.
Rh8 is possible but really doesn't anything because after 26. Rf5 white's h-pawn can still advance.  Black could have played c6! and it might draw but not sure.
! Now white starts to cash things in.
This must be played because of the threat of the Rf5-Bf4-Rg5 trio. Rh8 again does nothing because after Rf5! the pawn cannot be stopped.

!! This amazing beauty does the following:
1. Protects pawn and bishop (obvious)
2. I had envisioned the devastation if the rook and bishop swapped places and all the massive amounts of checkmate threats and sacrificial traps. This move allows that swapping.
3.  Does not let up any pressure on black and still keeps 3 of white's 4 pieces immobile.
4. Prevents Re5 which is the most effective way for black to halt white's attack in its tracks.  
5. Cannot be attacked by any of black's pieces or king.

? c6 was better.  This was definitely an oversight.  But still at this point black is lost.  
Black's best move would have been Re4! and I would have responded g3! and eventually h6 would still be possible. I'll update with actual lines later.
! Brings home the golds and diamonds it has worked so hard for.
Forced move.
Black's queen has 4 options one of them leads to checkmate (or loss of massive material) (Qf8) and the rest aren't much better.
Black chooses the lesser of the 3 other poisons.

There is equal material now but white holds a humonguous positional advantage.  White can win the knight by: 32. ... Qb4 33. Be5 Qxc3 34. Bxc3 and that knight is poof gone!   

A classic win!

21. Rg3 - Suddenly a dark dark shadow hovers over the black camp.  The BK suddenly feels very cold.  So he should if he does not look out then he will get a visit from the Chessic Grim Reaper Old Matey who is eyeing up the g7 square.  Black beats him off with g6.

31. Bb2 - white completes his development with a threat a nasty discovered check on the BK on the long diagonal.
33. Qf3 - white is back to being a pawn minus but is still making threats this one on the rook on a1.

34. ...... Ra8?? - the losing move black forgets that his rook walked away from an attack from the WQ just a couple of moves ago alas for him that queen and the threat is still there and now the BQ feels the white heat!
37. Qc6? - what about cxd6+ winning the BQ?

38. ..... cxd4 - black has a passed pawn but white is a R for P up black has no sufficient compo for the rook although while the queens are still on the board there is still the possibility of a snap mate on black's part or Ye Olde Perpetualle.
40. ..... d3?? - loses queen why not simply Qxa3?
42. Rd2 - white is taking no chances he blockades black's passer on d3.
43. ..... Kh6 - black tries to shelter his king but it is only a matter of time before Old Matey closes in!
44. a4 - after a second queen no doubt.
48. Kxf4 - Old Matey starts to descend right now!
49. Qg5 MATE!! - and now black cops it!  A sad end for my Class B opponent but many Kudos for Lalit for taking full advantage of his mistakes.
